<HEADLINE>
<P>
BALZER ON WINE: THE OTHER MONDAVI 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Robert Lawrence Balzer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINCE THE MONDAVI BROTHERS split up in 1965, much has been written about Robert 
Mondavi and his award-winning wines. But little has been heard of Peter and the 
Charles Krug Winery that the brothers once shared. 
</P>
<P>
This Napa Valley winery continues to be a family operation -- albeit Peter's 
family. His son Peter Jr., with engineering degrees from Stanford, helped 
design the winery's temperature-control systems and the computerized crushing 
area. Marc, the younger son, supervises 1,200 acres of some of the finest 
vineyards in the valley, including the winery's two choice vineyards in Los 
Carneros, from which the vintage Pinot Noir and barrel-fermented Chardonnays 
are drawn. 
</P>
<P>
Marc has worked at the winery since he was 10. "I did just about everything, 
jobs nobody else wanted to do," he says. "I learned from the ground up. It was 
the ground I liked best, the vineyards. That's why I went to UC Davis, to study 
viticulture and enology." 
</P>
<P>
Although the winery's fresh, fruity Chenin Blanc has always been its hallmark 
wine, it also produces superior Cabernet Sauvignon. As part of the 40th 
anniversary of its "Vintage Selection," the first private-reserve bottlings of 
Cabernet Sauvignons, Charles Krug released the '84, '83 and '81 editions. 
</P>
<P>
Some notes on the new releases: 
</P>
<P>
Charles Krug 1988 Chardonnay Los Carneros, $11.50. The bouquet suggests apples; 
the taste, lemons. This gentle wine will age beautifully yet is drinkable right 
now. 
</P>
<P>
Charles Krug 1985 Carneros-Napa Valley Pinot Noir, $8.50. Charming wine of 
jewel-garnet color with none of the tannic, tar-bitterness so often found in 
California editions of this varietal. Fine balance, remarkable delicacy. 
</P>
<P>
Charles Krug "Vintage Selection" Cabernet Sauvignon, $20. The 1984 is an 
intense ruby color. Vanilla in the bouquet adds intrigue to the still-youthful 
berryness. The California State Fair Wine Competition gave it a gold medal. The 
'83 has garnet hues, with hints of cedar in the bouquet. Good structure, but 
age will help. The loveliest of the trio is the 1981. This soft and elegant 
wine may be at its peak, but it will hold for several more years. Robert 
Lawrence Balzer 
</P>
</TEXT>
