<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: INTERNATIONAL LANGUAGE OF MOTHERS IS STILL GUILT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERMA BOMBECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There isn't a mother alive who doesn't empathize with Maria Gorbachev, who, 
during a recent interview, complained that her son, Mikhail, had not visited 
her in 3 1/2 years. 
</P>
<P>
OK, so the kid is up to his armpits in earthquakes, nuclear disaster, the 
threat of a unified Germany, civil revolutions, and Soviets fighting to leave 
the country. Not to mention the trouble he's having at the office and the 
shouting match between Raisa and Nancy that made the front pages. But is any 
one of them a reason not to call? 
</P>
<P>
Somehow it's comforting to know that Russian mothers engage in the practice of 
"glasguilt." We do have something in common. 
</P>
<P>
I happen to be a third-generation guilt-spreader -- maybe further back than 
that. But I can remember my grandmother (who could freeze-dry coffee with one 
look) saying, "I called you yesterday, but you knew it was me and you wouldn't 
answer the phone." 
</P>
<P>
My mother phones daily to ask, "Did you just try to reach me?" When I reply, 
"No," she adds, "So, if you're not too busy, call me while I'm still alive," 
and hangs up. 
</P>
<P>
I haven't done as good a job with guilt as my mother and grandmother. The 
reason for this is answering machines. My children dial my number when they 
know I am not at home. When I ask them why they never call, they say it is my 
fault for not having an answering machine. I wouldn't give them the 
satisfaction. 
</P>
<P>
I hate their answering devices. It is true that these machines are generally 
more polite than my kids, but I have never worked well under pressure. When a 
recording tells me I have just a few seconds to leave a message, I choke. 
Sometimes I just say, "Make me a grandmother" and hang up. The one that always 
gets their attention is, "You're out of the will if you don't return my call by 
-- " and then I break the connection. 
</P>
<P>
According to Maria Gorbachev, her son's visit in 1987 lasted just 40 minutes. 
Big deal. That's hardly enough time to remind him how long she was in labor 
with him. 
</P>
<P>
It's just a guess, but I suspect the entire time was spent listening to Maria's 
monologues on the following topics: "So, Mr. Big Shot, how come you never 
called? KGB got your tongue?"; "I might as well live in Siberia for all you 
care"; "You think you can replace my black-and-white TV with a color set and 
you won't have to bother with me"; "Oh sure, I could move to Moscow. Maybe 
you'd visit me in the bread line," and "I'm glad your father is not here to see 
how you treat your mother like a peasant." 
</P>
<P>
The woman has style. If Pravda's wire service doesn't get her son's attention, 
there's always "60 Minutes," Sally Jessy Raphael, Maury Povich. . . . 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA082690-0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 267052 </DOCID>
