<HEADLINE>
<P>
FESTIVAL '90; 
</P>
<P>
THE FESTIVAL AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles Festival 1990 grew out of the 1984 Olympic Arts Festival and its 
1987 successor, a not-for-profit event requiring three years of planning and 
the joint efforts of artists, communities and corporations. 
</P>
<P>
More than 1,400 participants from 21 countries are scheduled in 230 events at 
70 venues throughout Southern California, including 800 artists from the L.A. 
area. 
</P>
<P>
In many ways, Festival '90 is unlike either of its two predecessors: It focuses 
on art and cultures that rim the Pacific: Asia, Latin America and Oceania. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
This Issue 
</P>
<P>
Film, stage, music, dance, family attractions and visual arts are spotlighted 
in this issue. 
</P>
<P>
A schedule of programs from Friday's five performances and Saturday's 
multi-site Opening Day ceremonies to the finale on Sept. 17 runs on the borders 
of the pages. 
</P>
<P>
A map to locate festival sites is on Page 12; a schedule of Open Festival 
events today through Tuesday begins on Page 16 and a list of visual art 
exhibits begins on Page 20. 
</P>
<P>
The Open Festival, an adjunct to the curated festival, offers even more variety 
than its predominantly international counterpart, with 600 events at 400 sites 
by 740 artists. 
</P>
<P>
For recorded information on festival events, call (213) 688-ARTS; for ticket 
information: (213) 623-7400. 
</P>
<P>
Editor: Gail S. Tagashima 
</P>
<P>
Art Director: Tracy Crowe 
</P>
<P>
Listings: David Robertson 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
