<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: MY INDIA BY JIM CORBETT (OXFORD: $8.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jim Corbett served as a colonial administrator in northern India during the 
1940s, up to the time of India's independence and partition. 
</P>
<P>
The sketches in this volume of memoirs focus on his efforts to help the 
peasants in their struggles with poverty, disease, robbers, bureaucracy and 
wild animals (including the requisite man-eating tigers). Although Corbett 
writes with obviously sincere affection about "my friends, the poor of India," 
he patronizes them furiously: Secure in his status as a lord of the Earth, he 
surveys the humble and meek from his lofty vantage point. A curious souvenir of 
the final days of the British Raj. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
