<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRISIS IN THE PERSIAN GULF; 
</P>
<P>
IRAQ GIVES BRITONS WEDDING PARTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BAGHDAD, Iraq 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A British couple trapped in Iraq wanted a simple blue-jean wedding. 
</P>
<P>
But Iraqi authorities insisted that the Persian Gulf crisis should not prevent 
the betrothed from a more traditional Western wedding, including a champagne 
toast, a wedding cake and a white bridal gown. 
</P>
<P>
Thursday's ceremony was even broadcast on Baghdad television Friday. 
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to get married while here. . . . We are happy anyway," 
Deborah, the bride, shouted over Western music blaring from loudspeakers. 
</P>
<P>
The broadcast showed Robert (no second name given) in a dark suit kissing 
Deborah Janes in a white gown to the tunes of an Iraqi musical band and a 
children's choir. 
</P>
<P>
About 40 Iraqi "guests" and fellow British hostages wished the couple a happy 
life thereafter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
