<HEADLINE>
<P>
CANSECO, MCGWIRE ARE IMPRESSIVE, BUT FIELDER STEALS THE POWER SHOW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN HAFNER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There were 45,474 fans on hand Saturday at Detroit for the American League 
version of Home Run Derby. They weren't disappointed. 
</P>
<P>
The best power hitters in the majors, Cecil Fielder, Jose Canseco and Mark 
McGwire, all hit prodigious home runs. 
</P>
<P>
Fielder hit two and the Tigers beat the Athletics, 14-4. 
</P>
<P>
Fielder's first homer against Dave Stewart (17-10) came with a man on and 
carried 440 feet into the left-center field seats at Tiger Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
With one runner on in the fourth inning, Fielder joined Harmon Killebrew and 
Frank Howard as the only players to hit a ball over the roof in left field. 
</P>
<P>
Fielder has a major league-leading 41 home runs and 108 runs batted in. 
Canseco, who hit a 450-foot home run, has 35, and McGwire, whose homer reached 
the upper deck, has 33. They hit consecutive homers off Frank Tanana in the 
first inning. DAN HAFNER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, IT'S GONE: Cecil Fielder of the Tigers watches his second home run of 
Saturday's game against the Oakland Athletics travel over the left-field roof 
at Tiger Stadium. He leads the majors with 41 homers. C7 Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
